    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the length of the minor arc <m>ACB</m> in a circle with a radius of <m>10\text{ cm}</m> and a central angle <m>\angle AOB = 60^\circ</m>. Use <m>\pi \approx 3.14</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First, identify the given variables: radius <m>r = 10\text{ cm}</m> and central angle <m>\theta = 60^\circ</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Using the arc length formula:
            </p>
            <me>\text{Arc Length} = \frac{\theta}{360^\circ} \times 2\pi r</me>
            <p>
                Substitute the values into the formula:
            </p>
            <me>\text{Arc Length} = \frac{60}{360} \times 2 \times 3.14 \times 10</me>
            <me>\text{Arc Length} = \frac{1}{6} \times 62.8 \approx 10.47\text{ cm}</me>
            <p>
                Thus, the length of the minor arc <m>ACB</m> is approximately <m>10.47\text{ cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <figure>
                <caption>Diagram showing a circle with a radius of 10 cm and a central angle of 60 degrees forming minor arc ACB.</caption>
                <image>
                    <shortdescription>A circle with radius 10cm and central angle 60 degrees pointing to arc ACB.</shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]
                            \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (2.5);
                            \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                            \coordinate (A) at (30:2.5);
                            \coordinate (B) at (90:2.5);
                            
                            \draw[red, thick] (O) -- (A) node[midway, below right] {10 cm};
                            \draw[red, thick] (O) -- (B);
                            \draw[blue, very thick] (A) arc (30:90:2.5);
                            
                            \node[right] at (A) {A};
                            \node[above] at (B) {B};
                            \node[below left] at (O) {O};
                            \node[above right] at (60:2.5) {C};
                            
                            \draw (0.4,0) arc (0:60:0.4);
                            \path (60:0.7) node {\small $60^\circ$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The length of a minor arc is <m>15.7\text{ cm}</m>. If the radius of the circle is <m>12\text{ cm}</m>, find the central angle <m>\theta</m> that subtends this arc. Use <m>\pi \approx 3.14</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Identify the variables: Arc Length <m>= 15.7\text{ cm}</m> and radius <m>r = 12\text{ cm}</m>. Rearrange the arc length formula to solve for the central angle <m>\theta</m>:
            </p>
            <me>\theta = \frac{\text{Arc Length} \times 360^\circ}{2\pi r}</me>
            <p>
                Substitute the given values into the rearranged formula:
            </p>
            <me>\theta = \frac{15.7 \times 360}{2 \times 3.14 \times 12}</me>
            <me>\theta = \frac{5652}{75.36} = 75^\circ</me>
            <p>
                The central angle subtended by the arc is <m>75^\circ</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A pizza has a diameter of <m>40\text{ cm}</m> and is cut into 8 equal slices. Find the area of one slice (sector). Use <m>\pi \approx 3.14</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First, find the radius from the diameter: <m>r = \frac{40}{2} = 20\text{ cm}</m>. Since the pizza is cut into 8 equal sectors, the central angle <m>\theta</m> for one slice is:
            </p>
            <me>\theta = \frac{360^\circ}{8} = 45^\circ</me>
            <p>
                Now, apply the sector area formula:
            </p>
            <me>\text{Area of Sector} = \frac{\theta}{360^\circ} \times \pi r^2</me>
            <me>\text{Area of Sector} = \frac{45}{360} \times 3.14 \times (20)^2</me>
            <me>\text{Area of Sector} = \frac{1}{8} \times 3.14 \times 400 = 157\text{ cm}^2</me>
            <p>
                The area of one slice of pizza is <m>157\text{ cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the area of the minor segment defined by chord <m>AB</m> in a circle with a radius of <m>8\text{ cm}</m>, given that the central angle <m>\angle AOB</m> is <m>90^\circ</m>. Use <m>\pi \approx 3.14</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The area of a segment is calculated by subtracting the area of the central triangle <m>AOB</m> from the area of the sector <m>AOB</m>:
            </p>
            <me>\text{Area of Segment} = \text{Area of Sector} - \text{Area of Triangle}</me>
            <p>
                1. Calculate the Area of Sector <m>AOB</m>:
            </p>
            <me>\text{Area of Sector} = \frac{90}{360} \times 3.14 \times 8^2 = 0.25 \times 3.14 \times 64 = 50.24\text{ cm}^2</me>
            <p>
                2. Calculate the Area of Triangle <m>AOB</m>. Since the central angle is <m>90^\circ</m>, this is a right-angled triangle with base and height equal to the radius (<m>8\text{ cm}</m>):
            </p>
            <me>\text{Area of Triangle} = \frac{1}{2} \times \text{base} \times \text{height} = \frac{1}{2} \times 8 \times 8 = 32\text{ cm}^2</me>
            <p>
                3. Subtract the triangle area from the sector area:
            </p>
            <me>\text{Area of Segment} = 50.24 - 32 = 18.24\text{ cm}^2</me>
            <p>
                The area of the minor segment is <m>18.24\text{ cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A chord subtends a central angle of <m>120^\circ</m> in a circle with a radius of <m>6\text{ cm}</m>. Calculate the length of this chord. Use <m>\sin(60^\circ) \approx 0.866</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We can calculate the chord length directly using the trigonometric chord formula:
            </p>
            <me>\text{Chord Length} = 2r \sin\left(\frac{\theta}{2}\right)</me>
            <p>
                Substitute the given values <m>r = 6\text{ cm}</m> and <m>\theta = 120^\circ</m>:
            </p>
            <me>\text{Chord Length} = 2 \times 6 \times \sin\left(\frac{120^\circ}{2}\right)</me>
            <me>\text{Chord Length} = 12 \times \sin(60^\circ)</me>
            <me>\text{Chord Length} = 12 \times 0.866 = 10.392\text{ cm}</me>
            <p>
                The length of the chord is approximately <m>10.39\text{ cm}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In a circle with centre <m>O</m> and radius <m>14\text{ cm}</m>, a central angle <m>\angle POQ</m> is <m>40^\circ</m>. Find the length of the minor arc <m>PQ</m>. Use <m>\pi \approx 3.14</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Using the arc length formula:
                </p>
                <me>\text{Arc Length} = \frac{\theta}{360^\circ} \times 2\pi r</me>
                <me>\text{Arc Length} = \frac{40}{360} \times 2 \times 3.14 \times 14 = \frac{1}{9} \times 87.92 \approx 9.77\text{ cm}</me>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A sector has a central angle of <m>150^\circ</m> and an area of <m>235.5\text{ cm}^2</m>. What is the radius of the circle? Use <m>\pi \approx 3.14</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Using the sector area formula, solve for <m>r^2</m>:
                </p>
                <me>\text{Area} = \frac{\theta}{360^\circ} \times \pi r^2 \implies r^2 = \frac{\text{Area} \times 360^\circ}{\theta \times \pi}</me>
                <me>r^2 = \frac{235.5 \times 360}{150 \times 3.14} = \frac{84780}{471} = 180</me>
                <me>r = \sqrt{180} \approx 13.42\text{ cm}</me>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Calculate the area of the major sector defined by a central angle of <m>70^\circ</m> in a circle with a radius of <m>5\text{ cm}</m>. Use <m>\pi \approx 3.14</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The central angle for the major sector is:
                </p>
                <me>\theta_{\text{major}} = 360^\circ - 70^\circ = 290^\circ</me>
                <p>
                    Using the sector area formula:
                </p>
                <me>\text{Area} = \frac{290}{360} \times 3.14 \times 5^2 \approx 0.8056 \times 78.5 \approx 63.24\text{ cm}^2</me>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the area of the minor segment formed by chord <m>RS</m> in a circle with radius <m>12\text{ cm}</m>, given that the central angle <m>\angle ROS</m> is <m>60^\circ</m>. Use <m>\pi \approx 3.14</m> and <m>\sqrt{3} \approx 1.732</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    1. Calculate the Sector Area:
                </p>
                <me>\text{Area of Sector} = \frac{60}{360} \times 3.14 \times 12^2 = \frac{1}{6} \times 3.14 \times 144 = 75.36\text{ cm}^2</me>
                <p>
                    2. Calculate the Area of Triangle <m>ROS</m>. Since the central angle is <m>60^\circ</m> and the two sides are radii, <m>\triangle ROS</m> is an equilateral triangle with side length <m>s = 12\text{ cm}</m>:
                </p>
                <me>\text{Area of Triangle} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}s^2 = \frac{1.732}{4} \times 12^2 = 0.433 \times 144 = 62.352\text{ cm}^2</me>
                <p>
                    3. Calculate Segment Area:
                </p>
                <me>\text{Area of Segment} = 75.36 - 62.352 = 13.008\text{ cm}^2 \approx 13.01\text{ cm}^2</me>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A circle has a radius of <m>9\text{ cm}</m>. A sector formed by radii <m>OT</m> and <m>OU</m> has an area of <m>63.585\text{ cm}^2</m>. Calculate the measure of the central angle <m>\angle TOU</m> in degrees. Use <m>\pi \approx 3.14</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Using the sector area formula, solve for <m>\theta</m>:
                </p>
                <me>\text{Area} = \frac{\theta}{360^\circ} \times \pi r^2 \implies \theta = \frac{\text{Area} \times 360^\circ}{\pi r^2}</me>
                <me>\theta = \frac{63.585 \times 360}{3.14 \times 9^2} = \frac{22890.6}{3.14 \times 81} = \frac{22890.6}{254.34} = 90^\circ</me>
                <p>
                    The measure of the central angle <m>\angle TOU</m> is <m>90^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

